Fig. 4 a represents the hydrodynamic size distribution of the CQDs in the synthesized nanofluid, diluted with PEG 200. As shown in Fig. 4b, the hydrodynamic diameter (
d H
), which reflects the diameter of CQDs core and its protective shell, should be longer than the core particle diameter determined by TEM. The hydrodynamic size distribution is presented in Fig. 4a and shows the average diameter of 87.2 nm. High thickness of the protective shell (about 40 nm) accounts for the high dispersion stability of CQDs in PEG 200. Fig. 4c illustrates the optical path of laser light in the deionized water and the synthesized carbon nanofluid, indicating the Tyndall effect for the carbon nanofluid. Appearance of the optical path in the sample based on the Tyndall effect indicates formation of a very fine suspension (nanofluid). In other words, this experiment indicates that the reason for black color of the obtained sample is dispersion of CQDs in PEG and formation of the stable nanofluid.
